@startuml sequence_diagram

title Calculator — Sequence Diagram

actor User
participant "main()" as Main
participant "perform_operation()" as Op
participant "history" as Hist
participant "error_logger" as ErrLog
participant "cli_main()" as CLI
participant "CalculatorController" as Controller
participant "Calculator" as Calc

== Interactive Mode (no arguments) ==

Main -> Hist : clear_history() — wipe history.txt
Main -> User : "Welcome to the Calculator!"
Main -> User : display_menu()

loop until User enters "0"

  User -> Main : select operation (e.g. "1")

  alt choice == "13" (Show History)
    Main -> Hist : display_history()
    Hist -> User : numbered list of history entries
  else choice in 1–12
    Main -> Op : perform_operation(controller, choice)
    Op -> User : prompt for operand(s)
    User -> Op : enter value(s) (e.g. "3", "4")
    Op -> Controller : execute("add", a=3.0, b=4.0)
    Controller -> Calc : add(3.0, 4.0)
    Calc --> Controller : 7.0
    Controller --> Op : "7.0"
    Op --> Main : "7.0"

    Main -> Hist : record_entry("Add: 7.0")
    Main -> User : "Result: 7.0"
  end

  Main -> User : display_menu()

end

User -> Main : "0" (Exit)
Main -> User : "Goodbye!"

note over Main, Calc
  If a ValueError or ZeroDivisionError is raised inside
  perform_operation(), main() logs the error to
  calculator_errors.log via error_logger, prints
  "Error: <message>", and continues the loop.

  If an unrecognised choice is entered MAX_INPUT_ATTEMPTS times
  consecutively, main() logs the invalid choice, prints
  "Too many invalid choices. Ending session." and terminates.

  If get_number() or get_integer() receives MAX_INPUT_ATTEMPTS
  consecutive invalid inputs, it raises TooManyAttemptsError.
  main() logs and prints the message, then terminates.

  Invalid log base input in perform_operation() is also logged
  before falling back to base 10.

  History is stored in history.txt (local file) and cleared
  at the start of each session — it does not persist between
  separate sessions. Errors are stored in calculator_errors.log,
  separate from the normal operation history.
end note

== Bash CLI Mode (with arguments, e.g. "add 3 4") ==

User -> CLI : python -m src add 3 4
CLI -> CLI : build_parser().parse_args()
CLI -> Controller : _dispatch(controller, args)\n→ execute("add", a=3.0, b=4.0)
Controller -> Calc : add(3.0, 4.0)
Calc --> Controller : 7.0
Controller --> CLI : "7.0"
CLI -> User : "7.0" (stdout)

note over CLI, Calc
  If a ValueError or ZeroDivisionError is raised,
  cli_main() logs the error to calculator_errors.log
  via error_logger, prints "Error: <message>" to stderr,
  and exits with code 1.
end note

@enduml
